The book explores the development of radio astronomy from its origins before World War 2, examines many of the considerations that became fundamental principles of today's SETI operation (the 1.4 Ghz band for example) and traces the history of Frank Drake's efforts, beginning in 1959, to get a serious program of SETI started. It also discusses the implications of SETI in mature and sober scientific terms and presents the obstacles and challenges that have been partially overcome in the years since. It is extremely well-written and well-organized. Most public libararies have it and I strongly recommend it to anyone who is involved in SETI and, especially, to those who are actively involved in seeking government and private funding.     <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2660<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/7/02 8:49:08 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=651.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/nimoy.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: you are going to sleep</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>So we know the signal was clearly of intelligent origin. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
